Thought_Process: Because admissions are final each step, I should avoid applying first to a nursery where I will certainly lose the Step 1 seat to a higher-priority applicant. If I apply to Nursery_E first, I lose to Parent_B (higher priority at E) and then in Step 2 I would be blocked from applying to Nursery_B because it will already be filled in Step 1 by whoever applies there first (and I have top priority at B). By ranking Nursery_B first, I secure B immediately in Step 1 (I am highest priority at B), which is my best achievable outcome given that Nursery_E will be taken by Parent_B in Step 1. The remaining order follows my true preferences among the rest.

This is an immediate-acceptance (final admissions) process, so the key is to avoid “wasting” your first application on a nursery you are unlikely to win in Step 1, because you cannot later compete for nurseries that filled earlier. If you apply to Nursery_E first, you lose to Parent_E (highest priority at E), and then in Step 2 you can no longer apply to Nursery_C because it will have filled in Step 1 with you if you had applied there (you are top priority at C). By ranking Nursery_C first, you secure a guaranteed permanent seat in Step 1 (since Nursery_C prioritizes Parent_B highest), which dominates the outcome you would get by starting at Nursery_E. The remaining order follows your true preferences among the remaining acceptable options.

Because admissions are final immediately (no later displacement), the key is to apply first to the best nursery where I can actually win priority among those who will apply there in that step. If I apply to Nursery_D in Step 1, I lose to Parent_A (Nursery_D priority: A > C), and D becomes unavailable, wasting my top choice. Nursery_C in Step 1 is also unwinnable because Parent_B applies there and has top priority at C. Nursery_E in Step 1 is also unwinnable because Parent_E applies there and has top priority at E. Nursery_A in Step 1 is winnable: Parent_D applies to E, Parent_B to E, Parent_A to E, Parent_E to C, so I would be the only applicant to A and get permanently admitted. This yields Nursery_A, which is better than the likely alternative of ending up at Nursery_B (or unmatched) after being rejected from D/C/E while those nurseries fill in Step 1.

With final (non-deferred) admissions, the key is to avoid “wasting” an early application on a nursery you are very unlikely to win in that step if it will fill immediately with a higher-priority applicant. In Step 1, Nursery_E will receive applications from Parent_A and Parent_B (both rank E first) and you (if you apply). Nursery_E’s priority is E > B > A > D > C, so Parent_B beats both Parent_A and you; thus applying to Nursery_E in Step 1 guarantees rejection while Nursery_E becomes unavailable afterward. In contrast, Nursery_A is likely to be available in Step 1 (only you rank it first), and Nursery_A’s priority ranks you 2nd overall, so you will be permanently admitted if you apply there first. This yields Nursery_A, which is your best achievable outcome given the competition for Nursery_E. The remaining order should follow your true preferences among the remaining acceptable options.

Because admissions are final at each step (no later displacement), the best strategy is to apply first to the most-preferred nursery where I can actually be admitted given others' first choices and each nursery’s priority. In Step 1, Nursery_C receives only my application (others apply to Nursery_E or Nursery_D), so I am guaranteed to be permanently admitted to Nursery_C if I rank it first. This is my top true choice, so no strategic deviation can improve upon it.

With immediate final admissions, the key is to avoid wasting Step 1 on a nursery you cannot win. If I apply to Nursery_E first, I lose to Parent_B (higher priority than me at E) and E becomes filled in Step 1 anyway, so I gain nothing. If I apply to Nursery_B first, I am the top priority at B, so I secure B immediately in Step 1. B is my 2nd true choice and is the best achievable outcome given E is effectively unattainable. The remaining order follows my true preferences among the remaining nurseries.

Because admissions are final each step (Boston mechanism), the key is to avoid wasting Step 1 on a nursery you are unlikely to win, while still targeting the best achievable option. If you apply to Nursery_E in Step 1, you lose to Parent_E (highest priority at E), and then in Step 2 you cannot apply to Nursery_C because it will already be filled by you if you had applied there first, or by Parent_E (who has top priority at C) if they are rejected from E. By applying to Nursery_C in Step 1, you secure it immediately since Nursery_C ranks you #1, guaranteeing your 2nd-true-choice outcome. Any attempt to chase Nursery_E first leads to a high risk of ending up with a worse assignment (often Nursery_B or Nursery_A) because Nursery_C will be taken before you can apply in later steps. Therefore, rank Nursery_C first, then keep the remaining true preferences in order as fallbacks.

Because admissions are final and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, the key is to avoid applying in Step 1 to a nursery where you are likely to lose, while ensuring you apply early to a nursery where you can win. If you apply to Nursery_D in Step 1, you lose to Parent_A (higher priority at D), and then in Step 2 you cannot apply to Nursery_C because it will already be filled in Step 1 by Parent_E (C's top choice and C is Parent_E’s first choice). By instead applying to Nursery_C in Step 1, you still lose to Parent_E, but then in Step 2 you can apply to Nursery_D (which remains available because Parent_A takes Nursery_E in Step 1), and you have high priority at D among Step-2 applicants, securing Nursery_D (your top true choice). The remaining order follows your true preferences to the extent they could matter later.

Because admissions are final immediately (an early-acceptance style mechanism), applying first to a school where you have a realistic chance matters more than “reaching” for your top choice. In Step 1, Nursery_E will choose among first-choice applicants and you lose to Parent_B (higher priority at E). So ranking E first is very likely to waste Step 1 and leave you competing later only for schools that remain unfilled. If you rank Nursery_A first, you are the highest-priority applicant among those who would apply to A in Step 1 (Parent_E prefers C; others prefer E/D), so you secure A immediately. This yields your 2nd-best true option and is better than the likely outcome from ranking E first (where you would then be forced to apply later among leftover seats, typically ending at Nursery_D).

Because admissions are final immediately and you can only apply to nurseries that remain unfilled, you should avoid “wasting” your first application on a nursery that will be taken in Step 1 by a higher-priority parent. In Step 1, Nursery_C will receive applications from Parent_E (you) and Parent_B (who ranks Nursery_C second, so not in Step 1) and Parent_C (ranks Nursery_D first), Parent_A/Parent_D (rank Nursery_E first). So in Step 1, only you apply to Nursery_C, and Nursery_C will admit you (it has capacity 1). This secures your top true choice immediately; any deviation (e.g., applying to Nursery_A first) would likely fail because Nursery_A is taken by Parent_B in Step 2 if it remains, and you have lowest priority at Nursery_A. Therefore, submit your true preference order starting with Nursery_C to lock it in at Step 1.

Because admissions are final immediately each step, the key is to avoid wasting Step 1 on a nursery where you are likely to lose to a higher-priority applicant. The remaining order follows your true preferences among the remaining acceptable options.

Under this immediate-acceptance procedure, your Step 1 application is decisive because any nursery that fills in Step 1 disappears. Nursery_E is your top choice and you have 2nd priority there; the only parent ahead of you at Nursery_E is Parent_E, who applies to Nursery_C first (not Nursery_E). So if you apply to Nursery_E in Step 1, you are permanently admitted. Any strategy that does not rank Nursery_E first risks losing it in Step 1 to another applicant (e.g., Parent_A or Parent_D) while you are locked out from applying later. Therefore, submit your true ranking with Nursery_E first.

Because admissions are final and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, I should apply first to the best nursery where I can realistically win the Step-1 priority contest. Because admissions are final immediately and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, the key is to secure the best school you can realistically win in the earliest possible step. In Step 1, Nursery_E will receive applications from Parent_A, Parent_B, and you (Parent_D); Nursery_E’s priority order among you three is Parent_B > Parent_A > Parent_D, so you cannot win Nursery_E in Step 1. This guarantees you Nursery_A, which is the best achievable outcome given others’ preferences and priorities under this immediate-acceptance process.

Because admissions are final and each nursery fills immediately in Step 1, Parent_E should avoid applying first to a nursery that will be taken by a higher-priority applicant in Step 1 (wasting the first round). In Step 1, Nursery_C will receive applications from Parent_B (who ranks it 2nd) and Parent_E; Nursery_C prioritizes Parent_B over Parent_E, so Parent_E would be rejected if applying to Nursery_C first. Nursery_A will be taken in Step 1 by Parent_D (who ranks it 2nd) over Parent_E. Nursery_D will be taken in Step 1 by Parent_C (who ranks it 1st) over Parent_E. Nursery_B, however, is not anyone else's 1st choice, so if Parent_E applies to Nursery_B in Step 1, they will be admitted immediately. This guarantees a match and is the best achievable outcome under these final-admission rules given others' preferences and priorities.

Because admissions are final immediately, you should avoid “wasting” your Step 1 application on a nursery you are unlikely to win when many others also apply there. Nursery_E will receive applications from Parent_A, Parent_B, and Parent_D in Step 1, and Nursery_E’s top priority among them is Parent_B, so applying to Nursery_E first guarantees rejection. In contrast, Nursery_B is your 2nd true choice and you have the highest priority at Nursery_B, so ranking Nursery_B first secures a guaranteed permanent admission in Step 1. Any attempt to chase Nursery_E first would only push you into later rounds where your remaining acceptable options may already be filled, so the best strategy is to lock in Nursery_B immediately.

This mechanism is immediate acceptance: if you apply to a nursery and are accepted, it is final, so you should avoid applying early to a “safe” but lower-choice nursery if you still have a realistic chance at a higher-choice one. If everyone applies truthfully in Step 1, Nursery_E will choose Parent_E (its top priority), so you cannot get Nursery_E by ranking it first. Your best achievable outcome is Nursery_C: it will be available in Step 2 (since Parent_E takes Nursery_E in Step 1) and, among likely Step-2 applicants, Nursery_C ranks you highest (Parent_B is #1 priority). Therefore, put Nursery_E first (harmless even if you lose), then Nursery_C second to secure it in Step 2. The remaining order follows your true preferences for completeness.

Because admissions are final immediately, I should avoid applying first to a nursery where I have low priority and would likely be rejected after it fills, since then I lose the chance to apply there later. Nursery_D is my top choice and I have strong priority there (2nd), so applying there first gives me a good chance to secure it. If I miss D, Nursery_C and Nursery_E will almost certainly be filled in Step 1 by higher-priority applicants (C by Parent_B, E by Parent_E), so ranking them next doesn’t help much but is still better than worse options. Between Nursery_A and Nursery_B, Nursery_A is more likely to still be available after Step 1 (others’ first choices focus on E/C/D), whereas Nursery_B is likely taken by Parent_A in Step 2 if B is still open; thus I place A before B as the more attainable fallback while keeping higher true preferences ahead.

Because admissions are final each step and nurseries that fill in Step 1 disappear, the key is to avoid “wasting” early applications on nurseries you cannot win when they are still available. Because admissions are final immediately (no later displacement), the key is to avoid “wasting” an early round on a nursery you are unlikely to win in that round.
